explanation:
For each symbol: 
- fcntl: external system call that changes/reads file-descriptor state; needed to decide whether the F_GETFL/F_SETFL operations have observable effects (if they do, they are not dead). 
- F_GETFL / F_SETFL: constants used with fcntl; required to understand which flags are being read/modified and whether the operations are no-ops. 
- errno: inspected after fcntl failure to produce diagnostics; needed to decide whether the errno-based reporting has observable effect. 
- strerror: converts errno to a string for OS_DEBUG; if OS_DEBUG is a no-op, calling strerror may be dead — include to check side effects. 
- OS_DEBUG: macro/function that prints/logs diagnostics; must be known to determine whether the error-reporting branches produce observable behavior or are effectively compiled-out (dead). 
- OS_IMPL_SOCKET_FLAGS: the constant OR-ed into os_flags; if this is zero or already always set, the F_SETFL call (or its effect) may be redundant — needed to judge whether the flag-setting is dead. 
- OS_impl_file_internal_record_t: the concrete struct definition (fields fd and selectable) is needed to know the effects of writing impl->selectable and the meaning/type of impl->fd. 
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/function used to obtain impl from token; its semantics determine whether impl can be NULL/invalid and whether the lookup has side effects (affects whether preceding operations are necessary). 
- OS_impl_filehandle_table: the table argument to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its semantics may affect whether the lookup or resulting impl state make later operations observable. 
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: appears in the call graph and may be invoked by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — include to understand lookup semantics and possible side effects. 
- OS_SelectSingle_Impl: likely consumer of impl->selectable; required to determine whether setting selectable=true has any observable effect (i.e., whether other code reads that field to change runtime behaviour). 
- OS_SocketOpen_Impl and OS_SocketAccept_Impl: callers of this function (and potential subsequent users of the file/socket state); include to check whether the modifications performed here (fcntl and selectable) are relied upon by callers — if they are relied upon then the operations are not dead.

These symbols together allow assessing whether each executed operation in OS_SetSocketDefaultFlags_Impl produces any externally observable effect (system state change, I/O behavior, or retained program state read elsewhere). If an operation has no side effect and no other code's behaviour depends on it, it would be dead code under the MISRA rule.
